---
title: Pan-fried Sea Bream Butternut Squash Wedges and Garlicky, Bacon Kalettes
description: Introducing our veggie of the month: kalettes! These cute little green bunches are a combination of kale and brussels sprouts. Could you think of a more nutritious veggie? Kalettes make a great replacement for the more traditional brussels sprout. We think you may find them so enjoyable that they find a spot on your Christmas table (in place of the sprouts that is!).
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/pan-fried-sea-bream-wk51-28bfba92.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/pan-fried-sea-bream-wk51-598c192b.pdf
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/pan-fried-sea-bream-wk51-5810c874b0a36047b2603ee2
cuisine: Fusion
servings: 2
author: HelloFresh
nutrition:
  calories: 227 kcal
  fat: 8 g
  saturated fat: 3 g
  carbohydrates: 15 g
  sugar: 8 g
  protein: 26 g
  sodium: 1 g
course: main course
time required: 40 minutes
---

Preheat your #oven{} to 220 degrees. Cut the @butternut squash{600%g} in half lengthways (no need to peel) and use a #spoon{} to scoop out the seeds. Slice each half into wedges as thick as your thumb. Put your wedges on a large #baking tray{} and toss in a good splash of @olive oil{}, a tiny pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @black pepper{grind}. Pop on the top shelf of your oven for ~{35%minutes}, turning halfway, until nicely golden on the outside.

Meanwhile, remove any tough bottom from the root end of the @kalettes{1}(halved) (just like you would with brussels sprouts!) and then cut your kalettes in half. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one). Roughly chop the @streaky bacon rashers{3} into cubes. Rub a pinch of salt into the skin of each @sea bass fillets{2}.

Heat a splash of oil in a large #frying pan{} over a medium-high heat. Add your bacon and cook for ~{3-4%minutes} until golden brown and starting to crisp. Add your kalettes and cook for a further ~{4%minutes} and then stir in your garlic. Cook for ~{30%seconds}, then remove from the heat. Transfer to a #plate{} and cover with #tinfoil{} to keep warm. Keep to one side and wipe out your frying pan with #kitchen paper{}.

About ~{6%minutes} before your wedges are ready you can get cracking with the sea bass! Heat a splash of oil in your frying pan over high heat. Add the sea bass, skin-side down and cook for ~{3%minutes} without moving it, then turn and cook for a further ~{2-3%minutes}. Tip: By using a good splash of oil and not moving your fish in the pan, it prevents it from sticking to the pan! Your sea bass is cooked when it is no longer translucent.

Serve your pan-fried sea bass, butternut squash wedges and garlicky, bacon kalettes on a plate and tuck in!